scribes this stage of fetal lung development?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alveolar stage","Saccular stage","Pseudoglandular stage","Canalicular stage","Embryonic stage"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe features described are characteristic of the \u003Cstrong\u003Ecanalicular stage\u003C/strong\u003E of lung development, which occurs between weeks 16-26 of gestation. This stage is marked by significant vascular development and the formation of structures essential for gas exchange.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther stages include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eembryonic stage\u003C/strong\u003E (weeks 3-7): initial formation of lung buds\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epseudoglandular stage\u003C/strong\u003E (weeks 7-16): bronchial tree development\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esaccular stage\u003C/strong\u003E (weeks 26-36): formation of primitive alveoli\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ealveolar stage\u003C/strong\u003E (week 36 onwards): maturation of alveoli and continues after birth\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lung development occurs in five distinct stages: embryonic, pseudoglandular, canalicular, saccular, and alveolar.","The canalicular stage (16-26 weeks) is marked by vascularisation and development of air-blood barriers.","Type I and II pneumocytes first appear during the canalicular stage of lung development."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48690"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15932"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48690","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48690"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-20T11:22:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2